The paper deals with combinatorial optimization problems, which are typically studied in the computer science subfield of algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The focus on maximizing subsets and the use of profit functions suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the subfield of game theory (cs.GT). The consideration of similarity measures and the trade-off between good per-time solutions and stable solutions suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the subfield of machine learning (cs.LG) or artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Finally, the use of online algorithms suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the subfield of computational complexity (cs.CC).
